<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="devops-elk-beats-collection">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Deploy Filebeat and other Elastic Beats for log collection: file inputs, multiline handling, JSON parsing, Kubernetes DaemonSet autodiscover, processors, and shipping to Elasticsearch or Logstash.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>filebeat</tag>
      <tag>beats</tag>
      <tag>elk</tag>
      <tag>kubernetes</tag>
      <tag>logging</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>logging</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="devops-elk-architecture"/>
      <ref slug="devops-elk-logstash-pipeline"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Log Collection with Filebeat and Elastic Beats</title>

    <summary>Filebeat is a lightweight log shipper deployed as an agent on each host or as a Kubernetes DaemonSet. It reads log files, handles multiline events (Java stack traces, Python tracebacks), parses JSON, enriches with host/cloud/Kubernetes metadata, and ships to Elasticsearch or Logstash. Autodiscover providers dynamically configure inputs as containers start and stop.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Centralizing logs requires reading from many sources: application log files, container stdout/stderr, syslog, and cloud service logs. Filebeat's event-driven tail-follow mechanism handles log rotation and file truncation correctly. Kubernetes DaemonSet deployment ensures exactly one Filebeat pod per node, collecting all container logs without per-application instrumentation. Autodiscover eliminates the need to update Filebeat config every time a new service is deployed.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Collecting logs from files on Linux/Windows hosts where application code cannot be modified to ship directly.</item>
        <item>Kubernetes environments where all container stdout/stderr must be centralized without modifying application deployments.</item>
        <item>Lightweight collection without the Logstash JVM overhead — Filebeat ships pre-parsed JSON directly to Elasticsearch.</item>
        <item>Dynamic environments where new services are deployed frequently and Autodiscover handles configuration automatically.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Complex parsing that requires grok, translate, or conditional routing — Logstash or Fluentd are more capable processors.</item>
        <item>Kubernetes clusters where Fluentd is already installed and maintained — adding Filebeat creates duplicate collection overhead.</item>
        <item>Very high event rates (above 100k events/second per node) where Filebeat's single-goroutine harvester per file becomes a bottleneck — Fluent Bit has lower per-event overhead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="filebeat-inputs">
      <p>Filebeat inputs define what to read. The log input type tail-follows files and handles rotation. The container input reads Docker/container stdout logs.</p>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every Filebeat log input MUST set fields.service and fields.environment with fields_under_root: true so that these fields appear at the document root in Elasticsearch. Inputs for application logs MUST enable JSON parsing (json.keys_under_root: true) when the application emits structured JSON.</statement>
        <rationale>Fields not at document root end up nested under a fields object, making KQL queries require fields.service syntax instead of service, which breaks dashboards and alerting rules that expect flat field names.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Application log input with JSON parsing and multiline">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
filebeat.inputs:
  - type: log
    id: app-logs
    enabled: true
    paths:
      - /var/log/app/*.log
      - /var/log/app/**/*.log
    exclude_files: ['\.gz$', '\.zip$']

    fields:
      service: my-application
      environment: ${ENVIRONMENT:production}
    fields_under_root: true

    # JSON parsing for structured logs
    json:
      keys_under_root: true
      add_error_key:   true
      message_key:     message

    # Multiline for stack traces
    multiline:
      type:      pattern
      pattern:   '^\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}|^\{|^[A-Z][a-z]{2} \d{2}'
      negate:    true
      match:     after
      max_lines: 100
      timeout:   5s

    close_inactive: 5m
    clean_removed:  true
]]></code>
        <note>multiline.negate: true with match: after means lines that do NOT match the pattern are appended to the previous event (continuation lines of a stack trace).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="processors">
      <p>Processors enrich, filter, or transform events before shipping. Apply only what is needed to avoid CPU overhead on every event.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Processors: metadata, deduplication, debug log filtering">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
processors:
  - add_host_metadata:
      when.not.contains.tags: forwarded
  - add_cloud_metadata: ~
  - add_docker_metadata: ~
  - add_kubernetes_metadata: ~

  # Drop debug logs in production
  - drop_event:
      when:
        and:
          - equals:
              level: DEBUG
          - equals:
              environment: production

  # Deduplication fingerprint
  - fingerprint:
      fields: ["@timestamp", "message", "service"]
      target_field: "@metadata._id"
]]></code>
        <note>Fingerprint-based deduplication prevents Logstash retries from creating duplicate documents in Elasticsearch when a pipeline restarts mid-batch.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="kubernetes-daemonset">
      <p>In Kubernetes, deploy Filebeat as a DaemonSet so one pod runs on each node and collects all container logs from /var/log/containers/. Use ECK Beat custom resource for managed clusters.</p>
      <example type="good" title="ECK Beat: Filebeat DaemonSet with Kubernetes autodiscover">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
apiVersion: beat.k8s.elastic.co/v1beta1
kind: Beat
metadata:
  name: filebeat
  namespace: elastic-system
spec:
  type: filebeat
  version: 8.12.0
  elasticsearchRef:
    name: production-logs
  kibanaRef:
    name: production-kibana
  config:
    filebeat.autodiscover:
      providers:
        - type: kubernetes
          node: ${NODE_NAME}
          hints.enabled: true
          hints.default_config:
            type: container
            paths:
              - /var/log/containers/*${data.kubernetes.container.id}.log
    processors:
      - add_cloud_metadata: {}
      - add_host_metadata: {}
      - add_kubernetes_metadata:
          host: ${NODE_NAME}
  daemonSet:
    podTemplate:
      spec:
        serviceAccountName: filebeat
        automountServiceAccountToken: true
        terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 30
        dnsPolicy: ClusterFirstWithHostNet
        hostNetwork: true
        containers:
          - name: filebeat
            securityContext:
              runAsUser: 0
            env:
              - name: NODE_NAME
                valueFrom:
                  fieldRef:
                    fieldPath: spec.nodeName
            volumeMounts:
              - name: varlogcontainers
                mountPath: /var/log/containers
              - name: varlogpods
                mountPath: /var/log/pods
              - name: varlibdockercontainers
                mountPath: /var/lib/docker/containers
        volumes:
          - name: varlogcontainers
            hostPath:
              path: /var/log/containers
          - name: varlogpods
            hostPath:
              path: /var/log/pods
          - name: varlibdockercontainers
            hostPath:
              path: /var/lib/docker/containers
]]></code>
        <note>hostNetwork: true and dnsPolicy: ClusterFirstWithHostNet are required for Filebeat to resolve Elasticsearch hostnames from within the host network namespace.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="autodiscover">
      <p>Autodiscover dynamically creates inputs as Kubernetes pods start/stop, using pod annotations to customize parsing per service.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Kubernetes autodiscover with annotation-based hints">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
filebeat.autodiscover:
  providers:
    - type: kubernetes
      node: ${NODE_NAME}
      hints.enabled: true
      hints.default_config:
        type: container
        paths:
          - /var/log/containers/*${data.kubernetes.container.id}.log
      templates:
        - condition:
            equals:
              kubernetes.namespace: production
          config:
            - type: container
              paths:
                - /var/log/containers/*${data.kubernetes.container.id}.log
              processors:
                - add_kubernetes_metadata:
                    host: ${NODE_NAME}
                - decode_json_fields:
                    fields: ["message"]
                    target: ""
                    overwrite_keys: true
]]></code>
        <note>Pods annotate themselves with co.elastic.logs/json.keys_under_root: "true" to signal Filebeat to parse their output as JSON without a global config change.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="output-config">
      <p>Filebeat outputs to Elasticsearch directly (lightweight) or Logstash (when heavy processing is needed).</p>
      <example type="good" title="Direct Elasticsearch output with bulk and retry settings">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
output.elasticsearch:
  hosts:    ["https://es-node-1:9200", "https://es-node-2:9200", "https://es-node-3:9200"]
  protocol: "https"
  username: "${ES_USER}"
  password: "${ES_PASSWORD}"
  ssl:
    enabled: true
    certificate_authorities: ["/etc/filebeat/ca.crt"]
  index: "filebeat-%{[agent.version]}-%{+yyyy.MM.dd}"

  bulk_max_size:    2048
  compression_level: 5
  max_retries:      3
  backoff.init:     1s
  backoff.max:      60s
]]></code>
        <note>compression_level: 5 reduces network bandwidth by 50-70% for text logs at modest CPU cost; use on WAN links between Filebeat agents and Elasticsearch.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Deploy Filebeat as DaemonSet for Kubernetes node-level log collection.</check>
      <check>Set fields.service and fields.environment with fields_under_root: true on every input.</check>
      <check>Enable JSON parsing for application inputs that emit structured logs.</check>
      <check>Configure multiline for services that emit stack traces (Java, Python, Node.js).</check>
      <check>Set resource limits on Filebeat DaemonSet containers to prevent log collection from starving application pods.</check>
      <check>Configure SSL/TLS for all outputs (Elasticsearch or Logstash).</check>
      <check>Store credentials in environment variables or Kubernetes Secrets, not in filebeat.yml.</check>
      <check>Enable monitoring to observe event rates and backpressure from Elasticsearch.</check>
    </checklist>

    <see-also>
      <ref slug="devops-elk-architecture"/>
      <ref slug="devops-elk-logstash-pipeline"/>
